# PostgreSQL 18 Distribution

Target: @TARGET_TRIPLE@

This package contains PostgreSQL @POSTGRESQL_VERSION@ plus the extension set
installed into the same prefix.

Included dependency overlays:

- postgis_dependencies
- groonga
- fdw_dependencies
- v8

Installed extensions:

@INSTALLED_EXTENSIONS@

Installed tools:

@INSTALLED_TOOLS@

Skipped extensions:

@SKIPPED_EXTENSIONS@

Oracle Instant Client and IBM DB2 CLI are build-time/runtime inputs owned by
their vendors. When oracle_fdw or db2_fdw are built, this package includes only
the PostgreSQL extension files, not the vendor client libraries.

Runtime vendor clients can be installed after extracting the package:

- `x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu`: Oracle Instant Client Basic and IBM DB2 CLI/ODBC
- `aarch64-unknown-linux-gnu`: Oracle Instant Client Basic
- `x86_64-w64-windows-gnu`: Oracle Instant Client Basic and IBM DB2 CLI/ODBC

Linux:

```bash
sudo ./install_external_dependencies.sh \
  --oracle-basic-archive=/path/to/instantclient-basic-linux.zip \
  --db2-cli-archive=/path/to/linuxx64_odbc_cli.tar.gz \
  --service-name=postgresql18
```

MinGW64:

```cmd
install_external_dependencies.cmd ^
  --oracle-basic-archive C:\path\instantclient-basic-windows.x64.zip ^
  --db2-cli-archive C:\path\ntx64_odbc_cli.zip
```

Linux packages also install systemd templates under `share/systemd/`:

- `postgresql18-dist.service`
- `postgresql18-dist.env`

The package root includes service helper scripts:

- Linux install: `./install_service.sh [data_dir] [service_name] [service_user] [listen_addresses] [port] [auth_network]`
- Linux uninstall: `./uninstall_service.sh [service_name]`
- Linux external dependencies: `./install_external_dependencies.sh [options]`
- Windows install: `install_service.cmd [data_dir] [service_name]`
- Windows uninstall: `uninstall_service.cmd [service_name]`
- Windows external dependencies: `install_external_dependencies.cmd [options]`

Defaults:

- `data_dir`: `./var/lib/postgresql/18/main`
- `service_name`: `postgresql18`
- Linux `service_user`: `postgres`
- Linux `listen_addresses`: `*`
- Linux `port`: `5432`
- Linux `auth_network`: `192.168.0.0/16`

On Linux, `install_service.sh` creates the service user as a system user with a
non-login shell when it does not already exist. New clusters are initialized by
that service user, so the default superuser role is `postgres`. The installer
writes the listen address and port to `postgresql.conf`, and writes the host
authorization network to `pg_hba.conf`.

If the package is installed below a private home directory such as
`/home/user/opt`, the installer uses `setfacl` when available so the service
user can traverse the parent directories and execute the packaged PostgreSQL
binaries. If ACL support is not available, install the package under a
service-accessible prefix such as `/opt`.
